The distribution of \(Y\) is binomial with parameters \(n = 500\) and \(p = 0.25\). The goal is to find a lower bound for \(P(|Y/n - 0.25| < 0.05)\).

Using Chebyshev's inequality, for a random variable \(X\) with mean \(\mu\) and variance \(\sigma^2\), \(P(|X - \mu| \geq \epsilon) \leq \sigma^2 / \epsilon^2\), so \(P(|X - \mu| < \epsilon) \geq 1 - \sigma^2 / \epsilon^2\).

Here, \(X = Y/n\), \(\mu = p = 0.25\), and \(\epsilon = 0.05\). The variance of \(Y/n\) is \(\sigma^2 = p(1-p)/n = (0.25)(0.75)/500 = 0.1875 / 500 = 0.000375\).

Then, \(\sigma^2 / \epsilon^2 = 0.000375 / (0.05)^2 = 0.000375 / 0.0025 = 0.15\).

Thus, \(P(|Y/n - 0.25| < 0.05) \geq 1 - 0.15 = 0.85\).

This lower bound is valid for the binomial distribution since it has finite variance.

