The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for any one of the three drugs exceeds eight after 10 triples, with each drug having a success probability of 0.7 and trials being independent.

Each drug is tested 10 times, and the number of successes for each drug follows a binomial distribution with parameters \(n = 10\) and \(p = 0.7\). The probability that a single drug has more than eight successes (i.e., 9 or 10 successes) is calculated as follows:

- \(P(S_i = 10) = (0.7)^{10} = 0.0282475249\)
- \(P(S_i = 9) = \binom{10}{9} \times (0.7)^9 \times (0.3) = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821\)
- \(P(S_i > 8) = P(S_i = 9) + P(S_i = 10) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459\)

The probability that a single drug has at most eight successes is:
- \(P(S_i \leq 8) = 1 - P(S_i > 8) = 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541\)

Since the drugs are identical and independent, the probability that all three drugs have at most eight successes is:
- \(P(\text{all} \leq 8) = [P(S_i \leq 8)]^3 = (0.8506916541)^3 \approx 0.615729\)

The probability that the maximum number of successes for any drug exceeds eight is the complement:
- \(P(\max > 8) = 1 - P(\text{all} \leq 8) = 1 - 0.615729 = 0.384271\)

Rounding to three significant figures, the probability is 0.384.

