Problem: An urn contains four colored balls: two orange and two blue. Two balls are selected at random without replacement, and you are told that at least one of them is orange. What is the probability that the other ball is also orange? The unit of the answer should be  .
Solution: The problem involves finding the conditional probability that both balls are orange, given that at least one is orange. The urn has four balls: two orange and two blue. Two balls are selected at random without replacement.

The conditional probability is calculated as P(both orange | at least one orange) = P(both orange) / P(at least one orange).

- P(both orange) = number of ways to choose 2 orange from 2 divided by total ways to choose 2 from 4 = C(2,2) / C(4,2) = 1/6.
- P(at least one orange) = 1 - P(both blue) = 1 - C(2,2)/C(4,2) = 1 - 1/6 = 5/6.

Thus, P(both orange | at least one orange) = (1/6) / (5/6) = 1/5.

Evaluating 1/5 gives the numeric value 0.2. This is exact and requires no rounding.

