Problem: Calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons of wavelength $300 \mathrm{~nm}$ and compare it with a typical single-bond energy of $400 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$. The unit of the answer should be  $\mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$.
Solution: The energy of one mole of photons is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{N_A h c}{\lambda}\), where \(N_A\) is Avogadro's number (\(6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}\)), \(h\) is Planck's constant (\(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J s}\)), \(c\) is the speed of light (\(3.00 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}\)), and \(\lambda\) is the wavelength (\(300 \, \text{nm} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}\)).

First, compute \(N_A h c\):  
\(N_A h c = (6.022 \times 10^{23}) \times (6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8) = 1.197 \times 10^{-1} \, \text{J m/mol}\).

Then, divide by \(\lambda\):  
\(E = \frac{1.197 \times 10^{-1}}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 3.990 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol}\).

Convert to \(\text{kJ/mol}\) by dividing by 1000:  
\(3.990 \times 10^5 \, \text{J/mol} \div 1000 = 399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).

The wavelength \(300 \, \text{nm}\) has three significant figures, so the result is rounded to three significant figures, giving \(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\).

Comparison: The calculated photon energy (\(399 \, \text{kJ/mol}\)) is very close to the typical single-bond energy of \(400 \, \text{kJ/mol}\), indicating that UV light at this wavelength has similar energy to chemical bond energies.

